instance dt_constellation : DTDFVocab:Constellation [
    base:desc "The DT is orchestrated around a RabbitMQ message broker that serves as the central communication backbone. The physical side consists of a Raspberry Pi 4 running the controller and low‑level driver, which read DS18S20 sensors and drive a MOSFET‑controlled heatbed and fan. The digital side comprises: (1) a real‑time dashboard that subscribes to RabbitMQ topics to plot temperature and actuator states; (2) an on‑demand calibration module that triggers a calibration routine (Model B) when requested; (3) a Kalman‑filter module that estimates the unmeasured heatbed temperature using Model B and the sensor data; (4) a what‑if simulation engine that performs co‑simulation using the calibrated model; and (5) a self‑adaptation loop that, upon detecting anomalies, schedules experiments, re‑calibrates, and re‑configures the controller. Resource management is implicit: all components share the same RabbitMQ broker and the local network; the controller and driver are CPU‑bound on the Pi, while the simulation and Kalman filter run on a separate host. Coordination is achieved through message topics and a simple state machine defined in the controller’s statechart."
]

instance life_cycle_stages : DTDFVocab:EvolutionStage [
    base:desc "The digital twin for the incubator is developed in a sequence of clearly defined phases that mirror the typical CPS development lifecycle. 1) **Conceptual modelling** – two thermal models (Model A with two free parameters and Model B with four free parameters) are formulated to capture the heatbed and box dynamics. 2) **Calibration and validation** – Model B is calibrated against experimental data to better predict the heatbed’s thermal inertia; on‑demand calibration is planned to be triggered automatically during operation. 3) **Integration** – the physical twin (heatbed, fan, sensors, Raspberry Pi controller) is wired to a low‑level driver that publishes sensor data to a RabbitMQ communication server; the controller implements a bang‑bang logic with parameters LL, UL, H, C. 4) **Deployment** – the software stack (RabbitMQ, controller, driver) is deployed on the Raspberry Pi and the data are streamed to a time‑series database for real‑time dashboard visualization. 5) **Operational monitoring** – a Kalman filter runs on the digital twin to estimate the unmeasured heatbed temperature and detect anomalies. 6) **Evolution / self‑adaptation** – a closed‑loop self‑adaptation routine is defined: when an anomaly is detected, an experiment is scheduled, new data are collected, Model B is re‑calibrated, the Kalman filter is re‑configured, what‑if simulations are run to re‑optimize controller parameters, and the controller is updated. 7) **Continuous improvement** – the loop above allows the twin to evolve with changing plant behaviour, ensuring the digital twin remains an accurate, up‑to‑date representation of the physical incubator."
]

instance fidelity_and_validity_considerations : DTDFVocab:FidelityConsideration [
    base:desc "Model fidelity is evaluated by comparing simulated temperature trajectories against measured data from the calibration experiment.  Model B, with four free parameters, demonstrates superior fidelity in capturing the heatbed’s thermal inertia.  Validation is performed through on‑demand calibration: the system automatically runs a parameter estimation routine that fits C_air, G_box, C_heater, and G_heater to the observed data.  Verification is supported by a Kalman filter that continuously estimates the unmeasured heatbed temperature and flags anomalies.  Uncertainty is implicitly quantified by the residuals of the calibration fit; error detection is achieved by monitoring deviations between model predictions and sensor readings.  Quality assurance includes real‑time visualization dashboards, periodic calibration, and a self‑adaptation loop that triggers re‑calibration and controller re‑configuration when anomalies are detected.  These processes collectively ensure that both the models and the underlying data maintain high fidelity and validity throughout the DT lifecycle."
]

